Analysis of WNBA Salary and Performance Analysis (2024 Season)

Introduction

This report analyzes the performance of WNBA players in the 2024 season based on their salaries, Points Per Possession (PPP), Player Efficiency Rating (PER), and Win Shares (WS). I limited my analysis to those who have played 1000 or more minutes, to ensure only those with statistically significant playing time would be included. By examining how these players perform with respect to their salaries, this project aims to provide visualizations and insight into team outcomes and player valuations. With the increasing visibility of womens sports, I aim to offer a comprehensive review of player impact during the 2024 season.

Loading Libraries and Data

# Loading all necessary packages
library(dplyr) # for data manipulation
library(ggplot2) # for data visualization
library(stringr) # for string manipulation
library(scales) # for formatting labels 
library(magick) # for high quality scatterplot images 
# Loading in CSV data files
salaries_df <- read.csv("/Users/aasthaprakash/Downloads/wnba_salaries.csv")
stats_df <- read.csv("/Users/aasthaprakash/Desktop/wnba_2024_stats.csv")

Data Cleaning

# Modify column names to be more readable 
colnames(salaries_df)[colnames(salaries_df) == "Player..........................
                      ...................."] <- "Player"
colnames(salaries_df)[colnames(salaries_df) == "X2024.Salary"] <- "Salary"

salaries_df$Player <- trimws(salaries_df$Player)

# Function to format Player name into first initial and last name
format_player_name <- function(full_name) {
  name_parts <- unlist(strsplit(full_name, " "))
  if (length(name_parts) >= 2) {
    initial <- substr(name_parts[1], 1, 1) 
    last_name <- name_parts[length(name_parts)] 
    return(paste(initial, last_name, sep = ". "))
  } else {
    return(full_name) 
  }
}

salaries_df$Player <- sapply(salaries_df$Player, format_player_name)
stats_df$Player <- sapply(stats_df$Player, format_player_name)

# Select relevant columns from each data frame
salaries_selected <- salaries_df[, c("Player", "Salary", "PPP")]
stats_selected <- stats_df[, c("Player", "PER", "WS", "MP")]

# Summarize salaries by player, including PPP
salaries_summary <- salaries_selected %>%
  group_by(Player) %>%
  summarise(
    Salary = max(Salary, na.rm = TRUE),  # Use max instead of sum
    PPP = max(PPP, na.rm = TRUE)  # Include max PPP
  )

# Merge salaries_summary with stats_selected dataframes
merged_df <- left_join(stats_selected, salaries_summary, by = "Player")

# Convert Salary to numeric (removing dollar signs and commas)
merged_df$Salary <- as.numeric(gsub("[$,]", "", merged_df$Salary))

# Setting a minutes cutoff to only display those who have played > 1000 minutes 
minutes_cutoff <- 1000 

# Filter players based on MP (Minutes Played)
filtered_merged_df <- merged_df %>% filter(MP > minutes_cutoff)

# Find mean of Salaries
mean(merged_df$Salary, na.rm = TRUE)

The mean salary of WNBA players analyzed in the 2024 season is $100,710.50. This average provides a baseline for understanding player compensation across the league.

Data Visualization

# Create a custom theme!
custom_theme <- theme_minimal() + 
  theme(
    text = element_text(size = 14),
    plot.title = element_text(face = "bold", hjust = 0.5, size = 14),
    plot.subtitle = element_text(size = 12, hjust = 0.5), 
    axis.title = element_text(face = "bold"),
    axis.text = element_text(size = 12),
    panel.grid.major = element_line(color = "gray85", size = 0.5), 
    panel.grid.minor = element_line(color = "gray90", size = 0.25),
    legend.position = "none",
    axis.line = element_line(size = 0.25, color = "black"),
    plot.margin = margin(1, 1, 1, 1, "cm"),
    panel.background = element_rect(fill = "white"),  
    plot.background = element_rect(fill = "white"),  
  )

# Scatter plot for Salary vs PPP
ggplot(filtered_merged_df, aes(x = Salary, y = PPP)) +
  geom_point(color = "#8B0000", size = 1.5, alpha = 0.7) + 
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE, color = "#0072B2", linetype = "dashed",
              linewidth = 1.2) +  
  labs(title = "Relationship Between Salary and Points Per Possession (PPP)",
       subtitle = "Analyzing WNBA players in the 2024 season with 1000 or more 
       minutes played",
       x = "Salary (in USD)", y = "Points Per Possession (PPP)") +
  scale_x_continuous(labels = label_comma()) +  # Format x-axis labels
  geom_text(aes(label = Player), vjust = -0.8, size = 3, check_overlap = TRUE) +  
  custom_theme

Key Findings

The analysis of WNBA player performance in the 2024 season reveals key insights.

  1. Top Performer: Aja Wilson
  • Wilson consistently ranks at the top of all analyzed performance metrics, including salary, PER, PPP, and WS
  • Her salary ($227,30) aligns with her outstanding performance during the season, highlighting the teams proper investment in her
  1. Undervalued Player: Aliyah Boston
  • Bostons current salary ($75,792) is notably low compared to her high PPP, WS, and PER
  • She effectively contributes on the court yet receives less than the mean salary of those who played > 1000 minutes in the 2024 season, highlighting her as an undervalued player
  1. Overvalued Player: Kalia Copper
  • Coppers salary for the 2024 season was $241,984, yet her PER and WS are notably low
  • This disparity between her performance metrics and salary suggests that she is an overvalued player
  1. Legacy and Name Power: Diana Taurasi
  • Taurasis performance has declined compared to earlier in her career, but her salary remains high ($234,934)
  • Taurasis marketability, star power, and contribution to the WNBAs visibility may justify her compensation however, illustrating how factors beyond performance can influence salary decisions

Conclusion

This analysis of WNBA players in the 2024 season, examining salary versus PER, PPP, and WS, visualizes how player performance aligns with compensation. Through the visualizations, it is apparent that there is a need for more equitable compensation in the league. Reassessment of how teams are allocating salaries could potentially lead to improved team performance.

Beyond individual performance analysis, the data also underscores that name recognition and legacy play a factor in players compensation, regardless of current performance. Diana Taurasi is a prime example of this her legacy and marketability reflecting a broader influence on the league, fan engagement, and media attention.

To ensure fair compensation and the continued growth of the womens sports, the WNBA must continue to showcase the talents of current stars while recognizing the lasting impact of legends like Taurasi. By analyzing key performance metrics and salaries, the WNBA can bridge the gap between performance and recognition, driving greater visibility and investment into womens sports.
